You From?" recounts the unique experience of growing up in a place where the second generation seldom sees other people who look like them, and yet are inundated with popular representations of Blackness from the United States. This study explores how the second generation in Vancouver redefine their African identities to distinguish themselves from African-Americans, while continuing to experience considerable everyday racism that challenges belonging as Canadians. As a result, some members of the second generation reject, and others strongly assert, a Canadian identity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aAfricanszBritish ColumbiazVancouverxSocial conditions. 0aChildren of immigrantszBritish ColumbiazVancouverxSocial conditions. 0aStudents, BlackzBritish ColumbiazVancouverxSocial conditions. 0aYouth, BlackzBritish ColumbiazVancouverxSocial conditions. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / Marriage & Family.2bisacsh  a): African-Canadian.  abelong.  agender and blackness.  aidentity.  aracialization.  asecond-generation.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311069045340uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148753484440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487534844423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781487534844.jpg  a978-3-11-069045-3  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles